            <p>Well all of those cool buttons with those symbols on them all
          belong to the 'Tool Bar'. We use these buttons to help us move through
          our 'Scene View' and interact with the things that will be going in 
          our game.</p>
          
          <p>For example, they help us to move a box from one side of our screen
          to the next. </p>
          
          <p> Since we are going to be creating our game in Virtual Reality, or
          in 3D, we need to have a basic understanding of the 3 directions that 
          Unity uses. </p>
          
          <p>The 3 directions (axis) are:
            
            <ul></li>
                <li>X - horizontal (1st Dimension)</li>
                <li>Y - Vertical	(2nd Dimension)</li>
                <li>Z - Depth 	(3rd Dimension)</li></ul></p>
                <p> The z-axis is called the 'third axis' or the '3rd dimension'. 
                It usually represents depth, or the distance between objects. 
                With depth, we can tell how far away one object is from another. </p>
                
                <p>To understand this, put a finger in front of your face and focus
                on it if you can. The space between your finger and your face is depth. 
                You know your finger is in front of you, but you can't fully trace exactly 
                how much space is between your face and your finger by using a ruler, since
                the space between your finger and your eyes is different compared to the
                space between your finger and your nose.</p>
                
              <p>Now to help us move around the 3 directions in Unity, we have cool buttons
              to use. </p>
          
          <p>Below you will find the information on the buttons we will be 
          using while making our game. If you want to find out what each
          of the buttons do, click on *here* to go the help page for this
          chapter. </p>
              

